,Recommended,215530,8217772,"Posted: 22 December, 2013",all,hammer326,"I...really tried and yearned to love this game, as I do with every indie project that shows some semblance of original thought.I ended up...liking, if at times only TOLERATING, a lot of things about Van Helsing.Why do I say such a thing? because it got pretty bad at parts, but I also don't shy away from games totally unafraid to make me feel like a piece of♥♥♥♥♥♥like they did 15 years ago. This game succeeds on that front unquestionably.Ideally for 2-4 players, I actually just finished the entire game solo. Be forewarned, if you're not an ARPG guy, you're even in for a rough time on easy difficulty, which I all but mandate in your first playthrough. This game will swarm your♥♥♥♥♥like Starship troopers with things that do not, I repeat NOT, die in 1, 2, even 5 hits. It's rough, and it works for the setting and the game.Now at this point the average Joe has some idea of what they're in for, so maybe you ARPG die hards are now asking: ""What's in it for me?"" Well I'll tell you!Great music: I had to talk about this here. It's a standard we all have with games of substance, especially a good APRG. This game delivers EXCESSIVELY. The entire score features soft harps and pianos, things you would expect to hear in this alternative dark fantasy Transylvanian tale. Hit up youtube and hear some of it for yourself. This is one of few games that I actually left on while I wrote the review because of how great an atmosphere the menu theme provided.Story: One thing I found funny about a game as goofy as Torchlight 2 is that it took its Story as seriously as Diablo did. This flip flops- very believable, gritty, down to earth graphics, sounds, and atmopshere, totally slapstick everything else. The characters engage in light heartened banter while picking up quests, interacting with objects, and more.♥♥♥♥♥♥ there's even a message board in town at the beginning that is for nothing beyond ""click for great pop culture reference."" It's a true joy to experience.Gameplay: Not much not already said here, You are in for a challenge, no way around that. A fun challenge with friends, but a challenge. Bring your A game, this game's ""easy"" is NOT TL2's.Fresh and new ideas: Ever think how badass it'd be to properly have your own hideout/camp, or even gather resources and build♥♥♥♥♥♥in a game like an ARPG? well VH almost delivers. I can't say there's any proper crafting, but midway your township where your vendors reside can actually get attacked, and you play a metagame of tower defense to protect it. Very innovative IMHO, and successful.Overall, if forcibly shoehorned into rating it on a 1-10 scale, which I like to refrain from, I would call this game a 7 without question. Flawed, buggy still, but the devs care about the latter and are working on it, it's an all out riot most of the time, and most important of all- it's fricken $10 until the 2nd. Consider snagging it if you're a fan of the genre, or even a new guy looking for a semi hardcore trial by fire."
,Recommended,215530,8452262,"Posted: 31 December, 2013",all,Bl0rch,"This game is probably what the quick-to-judge would call a ""Diablo ripoff."" If you call any isometric hack and slash RPG a Diablo rip-off, then yes, this is it.However, it puts its own spin on the genre and taking a lot from what Diablo did well, and added some things it maybe could have used.You play as Van Helsing, of the Monster Hunter lore, as one of three classes: Hunter, Thaumaturge, and Arcane Mechanic; each with it's own set of skills and abilities. The monsters and creatures you face are the ever-familiar brand you'd find in any fantasy setting, such as Rat-men, undead zombies, giant behemoths, acid-spitting breeders, and even automatons. From what I can tell, the story is pretty straightforward and can be completed in about 15 hours, but that doesn't mean it isn't worth your time.The inventory system is top-notch, taking much from Diablo where you have to arrange your items according to their size and shape in a grid fashion. You are provided with a storage that you can access through the town areas and depending on your choice of perk, you can store more than just a single page.Your companion through the game is Lady Katarina, a ghost of someone who knows the Van Helsing line quite well. She can be customized to be completely support (no fighting), ranged, melee, defense, attack, etc. She can even be configured to grab items from the battlefield according to their type or value. She can be sent to the store (like a town portal) to sell loot she's carrying and even buy potions if needed.They kept with the waypoint system of using an ""ink gate"" which allows you to teleport to the various areas you've discovered, as well as use a town portal for yourself.There's plenty of side-quests and the various tasks to keep you busy (as mundane as they can be sometimes), the rewards are quite worth it.Each character has a skill tree that can be traversed as you gain levels by investing skill points. There are class-specific skills (main attacks and passive abilities), tricks (which are like sub-skills), and auras (which are passive bonuses). There's also a perk system that allows you to choose various character bonuses as you gain reputation (how well you're known around the land -- kill lots of stuff).The HUD and interface are very easy to navigate, it's very hot-key friendly, and the music/controls are top-notch.The game also supports multiplayer as well, so you can team up with friends to take on the monsters of Borgovia.It's not the most revolutionary game out there, but I think anyone who's a fan of the lore and liked Diablo (maybe even those who didn't) will enjoy this game."
,Recommended,215530,30859837,Posted: 31 March,all,_67alecto_OZ_,"Solid entry in the ARPG genre.  If you've played Diablo, Torchlight, etc then you won't see too much that is new.  Random items, set/unique items, packs of champion monsters, fetch quests, enchanter NPCs, imbuing socketed items with various items, and so on.My first time through, I played it on the harder difficulty so I got about 20 hours of game play out of it using the Hunter class.  There are additional modes like New Game+ (which they call neverending story) and Scenario where you have to complete maps with a timelimit while also achieving another task (never dropping below 50% health, looting all the corpses, or other things like that).Things I liked that may or may not appeal to veterans of the genre:When you disenchant something, you only remove the custom enchantment that was placed on it.  The item's base enchantments are not affected.  You can only enchant items once, so this is a nice balance.When you hover over an item, it tells you *exactly* how much better or worse it is compared to what you currently have.  It will show you impacts to spellpower, DPS, protection, Mana, HP, etc.If you put an essence in an item (the equivalent of a gem, element, etc that adds effects to your stuff), you can later pay to remove it without destroying the item or the essence.The only restrictions on item use are class and level.  So that thing that happens in other ARPGs where you're using the stat bonus on one item to allow you to use another item causing your stuff to become unwearable if you remove things in the wrong order doesn't happen.Respec'ing or reassigning ability points isn't an all or nothing process - there is standard cost to take back points or skills and you can play around with options on what you'll unlock before you are asked to confirm or cancel out.For a steam-punk/fantasy themed ARPG, Torchlight 1 and 2 are better, but if you can pick this one up on a sale like I did, you'll have some fun."
,Recommended,215530,8582479,"Posted: 5 January, 2014",all,StolenVex,"I found The Incredible Adventures of Van Helsing to be a fun Diablo-esc game.  I did not purchase the DLC, as I got this game on sale at a much earlier point in time and only played it recently.  I did play the game on a normal difficulty setting, single player only.  If you are looking for a review of DLC or Multiplayer content, this is not for you.Van Helsing is filled with hand crafted art and textures, fair story writing, and the occassional surprising content.  There are quite a few references to what I imagine are their influences in game and story design.  On the flip side, I felt like the gameplay was lacking.  I also felt like the story was developing into something exciting, and quickly sputtered off like they lost the inspiration to keep going.I spent the first half of the game excited and drawn in.  The second half I felt like the gameplay had devolved into holding down the right mouse button waiting for my skills to kill ever increasing numbers of the same types of enemies.  It took me about 20 hours to finish based on my play time.  I felt like the skill trees had some fun possibilities, but nothing inspired me to branch out from what worked in the first hours of the game.It was worth finishing the game to me, but I did feel this sense of, ""Was that it?"" --I don't know that I could recommend this game to everyone.  I felt like it was worth the sale price I paid for it, and the 20 hours I invested in finishing it.  If it matters to those reading this I do not feel like its worth a replay, and I am not interested in DLC for it.  If I was to attach an arbitrary number to the game in regards to a ""score"", I would probably say a 60%.  It doesn't fail to create a fun game to play, but it did lack some kind of wow factor."
