,Recommended,215530,34142559,Posted: 10 August,all,LeeboyPancakes,"Stop what you’re doing, do yourself a favour, just go buy and play this game. Or wait for a discount, it’s your wallet after all. I mean who am I to tell you how to live your life. I heard that they give you discounts up to 70%, which is always great. But this game is worth to buy either way.The Incredible Adventures of Van Helsing, to which I’ll be referring as “TIAoVH” from now on for convenience purposes, is a great game with it’s gothic/steampunk atmosphere and memorable characters. The game takes place in the 19th-century Eastern Europe where magic and weird technology is real. You play as the son of the famous vampire hunter Abraham Van Helsing and take on various adventures in order to defeat the reign of the mad scientists Dr. Fulmigati. Of course you encounter a wide variety of enemies from robots to werewolfs, harpies to mutant abominations on the way. I mean, come on, it wouldn’t be a Van Helsing game unless you get to kill tons of different mobs. Also, your lovely ghost companion Lady Katarina is there to help you out along your journey. The balance between the characteristics of charming and witty Katarina and more down to earth, serious Helsing makes the dialogue in game much more enjoyable.In TIAoVH you can use both melee and ranged weapons and make them viable on one character depending on your build. There are also other passive and active supporting skills for both Lady Katarina and Van Helsing. You can also switch Lady Katarina between melee, ranged and ghost modes. You can send her back to sell items when your inventory is full. Just like a Torchlight pet, but more useful most of the time. Also if you buy the DLC’s you get access to two more classes, Thaumaturge, a mage-like class and Arcane Mechanic, an engineer type class. All three classes have different skill trees and gameplay mechanics. The skill point reset system had some bugs that made changing builds a living hell, but the lovely developers implemented bugfix chat codes so they shouldn’t bother the player anymore.In some other reviews, I came across people comparing TIAoVH to other, similar games. Although I think it is completely natural to do so, there are couple of things they are missing. While comparing games the gameplay shouldn’t be the only aspect. The price tag, release date, the theme etc. should also be taken in consideration. And I’d say all things considered TIAoVH is one of the best games on the Isometric RPG market.Now, of course TIAoVH too has it’s cons. Personally, I love most of the achievements in this game. They provide you with some challenging gameplay and replayability. And while I am a big fan of challenging achievements, I can’t say I enjoy grindy achievements one bit. Not killing a single type of enemy throughout the game for an achievement, fun. Killing 500000 monsters to complete an achievement, not fun. But in the end earning achievements is up to the player. Some people might just say meh, while others like yours truly may spend over a hundred hours playing, chasing monsters left and right. Well, I think it was still worth it.There are times playing co-op feels almost impossible with constant bugs and crashes. The worst part is it completely depends on your luck. Sometimes me and my friends play for hours with no problems. But sometimes we crash so much that we eventually stop playing. I mean, it is still manageable. But if you’re buying this game to play with friends you better strengthen your nerves.Another downside of the game, to me personally, was the ending. They left it on such a cliffhanger that made it feel almost incomplete. But considering that there are three more TIAoVH games out there makes it a bit easier to deal with.All and all, I’d say this game is definitely worth your dime. It has great visuals and a good story. You can always spice things up with different challenges. And the game keeps you entertained with it’s perfectly timed pop culture references throughout the gameplay."
