,Recommended,215530,9952706,"Posted: 27 April, 2014",all,NMBR1MRTL,"When I first played this game it had a sizeable number of bugsand a punishing difficulty, even on normal. But it was fun.Four playthroughs later, after using all three character classes;the game is a mix of Torchlight II in terms of mechanics and asteampunk-ish Dark Souls, with its keyboard-bashing AI swarmtactics and overpowered monsters thrown at the player.The game has its sizeable number of bugs trimmed down to'manageable' number of bugs with its patch history, but bugsremain. Some of the achievements do not unlock even whenall the prerequisites have been cleared, only to be unlockedin a separate playthrough with another character or when alevel is loading between map screens.The writing in the game is, well; incredible. The introductorysequence alone leaves you wanting more with the variouslocations shown, but the witty banter between Van Helsingand Lady Katarina doesn't feel out-of-place in the grimlyrendered, industrial-gothic-overtoned world.With design elements from other great games and its owncombination of witty black humor and quirkiness, theIncredible Adventures of Van Helsing stands out well, morethan the sum of its parts.Recommended, but due to the bugs, proceed with caution."
