76561197993713200,Recommended,215530,9418568,"Posted: 11 March, 2014",all,Ỏ̡̲̗̬͚̥̾ͥ͟ͅ,"The incredible Adventures of Van Helsing ( an all dlc version review )This game offers you a choice of 3 different classes, each with a very solid selection of skills, first being a hunter which can actually be built in 3 different ways entirely on its own, or hybridized to your hearts content, having melee, ranged ( pistols and rifles ) and occult ( magic ) skills at his disposal.The second class is the Thaumaturge who is a pure spellcaster with plethora of skills at his disposal both offensive and control/support, all having their specific use, and the final class is a unique Arcane mechanic, having mine and grenade skills at his disposal, as well as gadgets and turrets.It is a very well done, unique and incredibly refreshing setting that this game is taking place in, there are no dwarves, no elfs, no typical fantasy arpg of which there is 16874 on the market and all look the same in the end.The game is set in a beautiful gothic noir setting with mythical, as well as mechanical creatures to be fought, and with exciting places to explore.Speaking about the monsters -They are designed well and look unique, there is swarms of them, so there is always alot of action, and thus, there is also tons of actually good loot, what more could you wish for, right?Speaking of loot, the itemization in this game is very well done.There is very typical item system of normal, magic, rare ( thus far the exact same as diablo II, including colors ) and finally epic and set items, which all have functionality like stat comparison to your equipped item, comparison to your followers equipped items ( more on that in a bit ) etc, a bit of a downside perhaps could be  that later on in the game, you may start getting lost in the constant stat comparations, because in this game it is fairly usual to be swapping items for new ones often.And what deserves a mention as well is that the devs were not afraid to actually let you drop or be rewarded with the epic items, one of my dislikes about other recent Arpg's is that you basically never get to see any of the highest tier items unless you farm for them for ages or play advanced game modes.This brings me to quest rewards, and money, since they go hand in hand.This is another area this game excels at. You get very, very good rewards even for sidequests you'd think were meaningless or not worth to bother with, being used to that from other, maybe even most rpg's.But in here, you are always rewarded with a rare item, sometimes in fact a unique ( epic ) one, with skill or stat points ( sometimes for you, sometimes for your follower ), and a decent sum of money, which are useful for quite alot of things as well.The experience reward for quests could I thought be higher, but then again, I reached the max level just playing the game normally, so there was no need for it then.And regarding money, another often overlooked area in other games, in here, you can then spend them upgrading your weapons, reseting your stat or skill points ( no other limits  for that then your money, awesome! ), gambling for items, and later on even improving the hideout where your character interacts with friendly npc's.Remember the mention of a follower? You indeed have one, bound to you by the storyline, and when I saw this, I was not happy about that, having experiences from most other games where followers are just constantly dead and useless.Not so in here, your follower, a ghost woman called Katarina has her own level progression with attribute points and 2 skill trees, one of which improves you by her actions/simply being with you, and the other purely improving her alone.This leaves incredible versatility and usefulness to her because you are completely free to make her an uberpowerful tank if you need it, and if it so happens she'd die, you can actually enable her to explode on death, usually clearing the whole mob of enemies that was attacking her.If you are melee, you are in turn completely free to make her your ranged support, or even if you so wish, to leave her out of the battle and just give you a permanent 10% dmg reduction.Furthermore, you could also tell her which items she would pick up ( if any ) and in which way should she attack your enemies, I wouldnt ask for more.Along Katarinas level up progression, and yours, which of course also lets you assign the typical attribute and skill points, there is more for your character than that. Much more.Along the regular skill tree ( or trees, for the Hunter class ), you also get an entire additional passive skill tree, which is in part unique and partially shared to/by all the classes, where you could choose from a number of passive skills two that you want to have active at all times.Want dmg reduction? Its there, want to heal Katarina with your attacks? Sure, and so much more.And thats still not all. There is an additional skill tree called ""tricks"" which you can also invest skill points, which are very useful active abilities like stopping the time, making 2 more katarinas temporarily to help you, or my spellcasters favourite, being able to burn all your mana for a massive explosion around him.Since the Thaumaturgist's spells are mainly focused on damage over time ( DoT ), this is a great tool to have for burst damage.Thought thats all? Nope, still not yet, because there are additionally perks too..You get those for killing big bosses and in general unusual monsters like veterans and champions, and they furthermore permanently improve your character to the point where you can choose to be impossible to be stopped in your tracks, or to not die when killed, and merely become incorporeal for several seconds.Now thats what I call a character progression, and to my best knowledge, I can honestly say it is unparalleled by any other single player Arpg's out there.The game as it is at the moment is imo a truly great experience free of any glitches or bugs, after being patched multiple times, which is incredibly impressive for a game studio so small that the final credits only rolled for about 1 single minute, no exaggeration.The game has very professional voice acting, as well as enjoyable music which deserves a mention, and the game is also full of very funny references to all kinds of things, including other games, of the same genre or otherwise, sometimes fairly hidden, sometimes very obvious.Some games may try to make jokes which dont fit in it, or some games just go full ""funny"" all the way, but what is impressive  about this game is that it manages to have an interesting, serious, believable world and atmosphere, and yet, effortlessly manages to include funny references in it that just make you smile..The games lenght is very solid 18 hours for one playthrough which is great, considering there are scenario mode and a game+ mode available as well, so replayability is great.Sumarry: An amazing action rpg game that has been a ton of pure fun thanks to its for a single player rpg unrivaled character development options, unique setting, fluent game mechanics that are clear and work exactly as youd expect at all times, and thanks to the constant rewards the game gives you which will never make you leave it for long until youve seen it all.And that would take at least a while.Highly recommended to get, the developers really deserve to be rewarded for a game this polished and with this many gameplay features.Rating: 89/100Pros:Unique settingCharacter developmentUseful followerItem types, customization optionsNpc functionalitiesGame's lasting appealSmart, funny referencesMade by a very small team, yet feeling as an AAA title forCons:Recycling of enemies in some levelsSometimes can become messy with swarms of enemies aroundStat comparing may feel a bit confusing"
76561197990499249,Recommended,215530,8487614,"Posted: 1 January, 2014",all,szubin0020,"its gooood, better than dugeon siege and much cheaper and almost as good as torchlight :)"
,Recommended,215530,10507610,"Posted: 17 June, 2014",all,dc,"Totally awesome action RPG. Without revealing too much of the story, you are the son of Van Helsing and aided by your ghostly companion Katarina, you travel to the distant land of Borgovia to rid the evil there. Gameplay reminds me a lot of Torchlight but the level of customization is a bit higher and the skill tree provides some nice upgrades. There is also a perk system which greatly enhances gameplay imo (depending on which perks you choose). Controls can be daunting at first, but as you go along and experiment with different skill sets, you will find the best option  that works for you. As previously mentioned, other classes are only available as a separate DLC, hence you should only buy this game as a full bundle (when it is on sale of course). The other DLCs add some much needed upgrades and modifications to an already cool game. Plus, when you've beaten this game you can import your character into The Incredible Adventures of Van Helsing 2 and continue the adventure! :D"
