76561198029180753,Not Recommended,215530,9509460,"Posted: 16 March, 2014",all,mmx30714,"The experience of playing The Incredible Adventures of Van Helsing (TIOAVH), is like Diablo II but not as fun as Diablo II; as I continue to expand on my review, you will hear the ""like Diablo II but"" comparison quite often, with that in mind, let's get rolling.The Story campaign spilts into 3 chapters in TIOAVH, though in terms of map variation and sizes it only counts as two and a half since many areas are just a small pocket map and one map got used twice with different mobs. Like Diabo II, you'll fight a defining boss like mob at the end of each chapter which will then transition you to the next act, but not only is the campaign much shorter, the combat is much less fulfilling. In Diablo II, you play as the nameless hero conquering the demons, the fact that you remain nameless is what allows the player to fill in the void with their own imagination and make the experience their own; in TIOAVH, the main character is a decendant of Van Helsing, attempting to rid the town of Borgovia of a mad scientist. The player is just a Van Helsing Jr trying to make his own. Even though the story of TIOAVH has no fatal flaw, personally, Diablo II's story is much better.Class wise, TIOAVH only have 1 (3 with expansion) character to choose from, unlike the 5 (7 with expansion) character available in Diabo II. On top of that, the additional two character, arguably, has very similar style, elemental long range attack, so personally, I'd consider them the same addition but with a slight variation. Point Diablo II.Map wise TIOAVH doesn't have a lot to offer, in fact, most of the ink map are just mix and mash of the regular map, and one map you even visited twice; Diabo II on the otherhand offers a complete change of scenary, from grass field to desert to a swamp. Point Diablo II.AI/combat wise, TIOAVH suffers a blow back. Mob will either try to shoot you or rush you until they drop, which often result in the tactic commonly know as the ""run you♥♥♥♥♥off, till the enemy dies"", which could get faily repetitive fairly fast. Diablo on the other hand have enemy which fleeing, and even at one point, friendly NPC. Point Diablo II.To sum it up, if you're haven't play Diablo II, and you're interested in these type of action RPG, then you should definitely skip and give Diablo II a shot; if however, you're addicted to action RPG game and can't find any other action RPG out there, then suppose TIOVAH could tie you over until your next fix."
