76561197970734669,Recommended,215530,26667966,"Posted: 18 November, 2016",all,Happeh,"The game is a 4/5. It has some weak points, but it is easily worth $10 if it is available on sale. The weak points are mostly minor things.The game mechanics needed better planning. There are a variety of upgrades for the weapons, but there is no point in getting anything but the base gun upgrade, the ice upgrade, and the explosion upgrade. A person could use the scatter or poison upgrades for enjoyment, but there is no reason to. Same goes for the spell upgrade tree. Ignore them and use the explosion upgrade unless you want variety for your own enjoyment.The voice acting is kind of silly. I have never understood why games use voice actors who do a poor job attempting a foreign accent, instead of just hiring someone who really has an accent. There are some quality control problems with the dialog not matching the subtitling.Item pickups are strange. An item might be found at level 10 that is better than items found all the way up to level 20. I think I used a level 20 gun all the way up to level 30 because none of the guns from levels 21 through 30 were any better, even though they were the highest level yellow weapons, and the level 20 gun was just a blue level gun. There is a ring at level 16 or so that boosts mana, hit points and rage to such high levels that it would make no sense to replace it with any other ring no matter how high it's level was. I felt disappointment every time I picked up a yellow ring and had to sell it because there was no place to put it.There are a few spots where it is impossible to get through without dying, which really irks me. The situations are of the variety ""teleport into a setting with 20 guys 4 feet away from you, and if you try running there are 20 more guys 10 feet away in every direction"". I want challenges, but impossible situations are cheating.Other than those minor points, the settings are interesting and well done, the graphics look good, the game engine plays well, the enemy design is varied and challenging, and the music was addicting. I found myself turning the game on just so I could hear the main music play over and over again."
