,Recommended,215530,17274078,"Posted: 28 July, 2015",all,Malvadanya,"Se for pra jogar coop sim, a não ser..."
,Recommended,215530,17342826,"Posted: 1 August, 2015",all,malkav11,"I'd heard very mixed things about The Incredible Adventures of Van Helsing, but I do enjoy a good ARPG and this one had a unique setting and some interesting mechanics to recommend it, so I gave it a go. I'm surely glad I did, because Van Helsing is one of my favorite ARPGs to date. Now, I know a lot of people go into these games looking primarily at theorycrafting builds and chasing loot. If you're one of those people, take my opinions with a grain of salt because that isn't what I get out of them at all. Oh, sure, making my numbers go up is a hook in any RPG and I get a basic pleasure out of that sort of thing, but I need something more than that to make loot genuinely compelling - unique modifiers like Diablo 3's legendaries or Marvel Heroes' uniques and artifacts, that sort of thing. And I'm not going to replay the game enough to really tweak a build into optimal form. I just want a variety of classes with cool powers that give visceral feedback when I use them.Van Helsing's loot is capable enough - a spread of rarities including epic and set gear (and, though I didn't see any, legendaries), an enchantment system, a separate ""essence"" system, a forge where you can feed unwanted gear to roll new items (and later get some control over what you're crafting), a gambling vendor, etc. Fairly standard Diablo-type fare, no notable lack but none of the unique effect hooks that really get my motor running. Classes are definitely fun - I played an Arcane Mechanic and chucked around grenades while spawning turrets and mechanical spiders, but I could have gone a bunch of other ways or tried the base game Hunter (a traditional monster hunter with sword and gun) or the other DLC class, the Thaumaturge (an occult specialist). And the skill system seems robust and innovative, with various temporary powerups to pump rage into on your primary skills and expertise bonuses you can buy into to further improve your favored abilities, as well as a stacking bonus to everything whenever you spend skill points in your main tree and bonuses at certain thresholds. Beyond that, there's a ""reputation"" track to level by killing champions and bosses that lets you select perks to further customize your build, unlocked by achieving various criteria during the game. And once you've hit the level cap there's even a ""glory"" system for further tweaking your character in post-story modes.So all that's well and good. But really, what sold me on the game is the story mode itself. Oh, it's not a tremendously deep or nuanced story, although it's a bit more creative and interesting than the typical ARPG story. But it takes you through dozens of handmade, beautiful, atmospheric levels that are densely packed with monsters, quests, and secrets. And treasure, of course. The game really rewards you for digging into every last nook and cranny of every map and talking to all the NPCs, triggering special bosses, rare loot drops, stat rewards and more. As someone who really enjoys exploration in videogames, this is exactly the sort of thing I am clamoring for."
