,Recommended,215530,24578785,"Posted: 28 July, 2016",all,Twitine,"Setting/Story:The game seemed outdated when I saw it, and graphically is, but I was drawn by the steampunk and demonic/occult influences. And the levels and characters really show a depth of artistic direction. It provides a very varied level setting and enemy types, which surprised me for such an old RPG. The story was very well thought out, the voice acting suberb. While I mostly hurried through the dialogue, the humorous and quirky banter was captivating. The setting and story so far is perfect, miles better than Diablo 3, of which nothing was memorable.Cost:+ $5 on steam sale- You need to spend extra for DLCFun:+ The skill trees/stat buildup/perks are varied and interesting for the main character+ The hunter class can be specced creatively into multiple effective options+ Multiplayer+/- 2 other classes but you must buy them- Support ghost not as interesting to levelNote on Final Cut Edition:There is a Final Cut edition, which condenses all three Van Helsing games into one, with the six classes of the final game. I only bought the first game to check it out and would recommend you do the same. For me the joy of playing these games comes from the skill tree and forging your own build, so by playing each game separately and not as one whole, you get to start fresh at every new game, which is much more fun and varied than being stuck in one class for 3 games. You get the final cut for free if you redeem it after you buy all three games so it is the best option anyhow.I'm probably going to get the second game soon and will update this review on how it goes. For a $5 game, it gives me a much better experience than Diablo 3. I'm quite excited that I found this gem actually - the rating was mixed and below satisfactory. Perhaps its was that at a full launch price."
